data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3+ supports **ValueTuple** with `DynamicData`, eliminating the `object[]` boxing:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — compile-time type checking, no casts
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple literals instead of array literals

This requires **MSTest 3.4+** (`Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting`). The test method signature stays the same — MSTest destructures the tuple into the parameters automatically.
